# Project: Verifiable Research Integrity Platform (AuditWiz)
# Architecture: Next.js + Supabase + Blockchain Anchoring
# Collaboration & ORCID Identity Expansion Rules
# Scope: Research-grade integrity system designed to be clinical-ready by design (not regulatory compliant yet)

---
## 🔐 Integrity First

- Records are immutable.
- Amendments create new versions.
- Audit log is append-only.
- No UPDATE or DELETE on audit events.

## 🧬 ORCID Identity Rules

- ORCID identity is immutable once linked.
- ORCID linking must generate audit event.
- Only one ORCID ID per user.
- ORCID badge must be displayed where attribution is shown.
- Invite-by-ORCID must bind to ORCID ID, not just email.

## 🔐 Core Architectural Principles (Non-Negotiable)

1. No record is ever overwritten (after submission).
   - Draft records may be updated in-place; each save emits record_draft_updated.
   - After submission, updates must create new versions (amendment model).

2. All significant actions must emit an audit event.
   - Insert-only audit ledger.
   - No UPDATE or DELETE on audit events.
   - Audit log is append-only and immutable.

3. All actions must be attributable to a verified individual or system actor.
   - No anonymous actions.
   - Role at time of action must be captured.
   - AI/system actions must be clearly labeled as system actors.

4. Human authority overrides automation.
   - AI may suggest, summarize, or flag.
   - AI may NOT finalize, approve, or anchor records.
   - Approval requires authenticated human signature.

5. Blockchain is an integrity anchor, not a data store.
   - Never store PHI or sensitive data on-chain.
   - Only store hashes.
   - Prefer batching (Merkle roots) over per-record anchors where possible.

6. Design for future algorithm agility.
   - Store signature algorithm type.
   - Prepare for future PQC integration.
   - Do not hardcode cryptographic assumptions.

---

## 🧠 AI Usage Guidelines

- AI outputs must be logged as audit events.
- Log:
  - model version
  - input hash
  - output hash
- AI cannot:
  - Approve records
  - Modify immutable content
  - Change role permissions
  - Override workflow states

AI is advisory-only.

---

## 🔑 Access Control Rules

- Roles are scoped per study (not global).
- Enforce permissions at:
  - Supabase RLS layer
  - API layer
  - UI visibility layer
- Never rely on frontend-only authorization.

Allowed roles:
- creator
- reviewer
- approver
- auditor
- admin

All permission checks must occur server-side.

---

## 👥 Study Member Controls

- Roles are study-scoped.
- Permission flags must be enforced server-side.
- RLS must reflect permission flags.
- No frontend-only permission logic.


---

## 🤝 Collaboration Rules

- All collaboration must be attributable.
- No anonymous actions.
- No shared mutable drafts.
- Shared artifacts are read-only.
- Sharing must log access events.
- Share tokens must be hashed in DB.
---

## 📚 Study & Record Rules

Study lifecycle states:
- draft
- active
- locked
- archived

Locked studies:
- No new records
- No amendments
- Only exports and anchor verification allowed

Record lifecycle states:
- draft
- submitted
- under_review
- approved
- locked
- anchored

Transitions must be validated server-side.

---

## ✍️ Electronic Signature Requirements

- Signing requires re-authentication.
- Signature must include:
  - signer ID
  - signer role
  - timestamp
  - signature intent
  - record version hash
- Signature is immutable once created.

No silent approvals.

---

## 📦 Document Handling Rules

- Store documents in Supabase Storage.
- Always compute and store content hash.
- Never trust filename alone.
- Hash must be logged in audit event.

Do not allow document replacement — require new version upload.

---

## ⛓ Blockchain Anchoring Rules

- Anchoring only allowed for approved records.
- Anchor only content hash.
- Store:
  - tx hash
  - chain ID
  - timestamp
- Do not block record usage if chain RPC fails — fallback to DB anchor entry.

Private keys:
- Must only exist in server environment variables.
- Never expose via NEXT_PUBLIC.
- Never log private key.

---

## 🛑 Prohibited Changes

Cursor must NOT:

- Introduce direct UPDATE or DELETE on audit_events.
- Introduce inline record edits for non-draft records (draft edits are allowed and must emit record_draft_updated).
- Add blockchain storage of raw content.
- Add client-side-only permission checks.
- Claim regulatory compliance in code comments or UI.
- Introduce PHI handling logic.

---

## 🧾 Logging Requirements

Every meaningful action must produce an audit event:
- record_created
- record_draft_updated (draft saves; includes last_edited_by, last_edited_at)
- record_amended
- record_submitted
- record_approved
- record_rejected
- signature_created
- document_uploaded
- blockchain_anchored
- role_assigned
- role_revoked
- ai_analysis_performed

---

## 📤 Sharing Constraints

- Shared records are version-specific.
- Shared links must support expiration.
- No amendment via share link.
- No recursive sharing.

Private keys must never appear in logs or responses.

---

## 🧩 Design Philosophy

This is not a collaboration app.
This is not a generic document manager.
This is a verifiable research integrity system.

All new features must strengthen:
- Traceability
- Immutability
- Attribution
- Transparency
- Long-term verifiability

If a feature weakens integrity guarantees, it must be rejected.

---

## 📈 Future Expansion Guardrails

The system should remain extensible for:
- Clinical trial workflows
- PQC signature algorithms
- Merkle batch anchoring
- Risk-based AI monitoring
- Multi-institution federation

But MVP scope must remain controlled.

---

# End of Rules